    <p><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a></p>

    <h1>Love of the high seas runs in the fam&#xAD;ily</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <time datetime="2021-01-12"><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210112/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-12">2021-01-12</a></time> -
        Clara Lock

            <a href="/category/tag-536891167/en/sg">Malaysia</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068228/en/sg">Thailand</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537260725/en/sg">Republic Polytechnic</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-536891206/en/sg">Singapore</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068150/en/sg">Iceland</a>     </section>

        <p>Some of Ms Ariel Soeigia­rto’s best child­hood memories were of be­ing out on the wa­ter with her fa­ther Roy Soeigia­rto, fish­ing and boat­ing lo­cally as well as in Malaysia and Thai­land.</p>
        <p>It sparked a love of the sea and out­doors for the 20-year-old, who grad­u­ated from Repub­lic Polytech­nic with a diploma in de­sign for user ex­pe­ri­ence last year.</p>
        <p>As a direc­tor at Kairos Strate­gic – a re­gional dis­trib­u­tor of boats for safety, res­cue and se­cu­rity use – she saw a new mar­ket for the decade-old busi­ness that her fa­ther, 49, founded.</p>
        <p>In Oc­to­ber, the pair rolled out coastal rides in a rigid hull in­flat­able boat (RHIB), nor­mally used for high-speed mil­i­tary and emer­gency op­er­a­tions.</p>
        <p>Hav­ing gone out on her fa­ther’s boats with fam­ily and friends from a young age, Ms Soeigia­rto knew the rides would ap­peal to civil­ians too.</p>
        <p>Her friends were amazed by the waters around Sin­ga­pore, she re­calls, some of them ex­plor­ing the is­land’s wa­ter­ways for the first time.</p>
        <p>“Dur­ing his­tory lessons, we</p>
        <p>learnt about Sin­ga­pore’s mar­itime trade, her­itage and port ser­vices, yet peo­ple don’t get to see this side of the coun­try first hand,” says the el­dest of four chil­dren, whose mother is a housewife in her 40s.</p>
        <p>Fast and sta­ble, the RHIB can cover more ground than fer­ries</p>
        <p>that typ­i­cally ply the South­ern Is­lands’ route and are far more ex­cit­ing, as I dis­cov­ered re­cently when I took a ride on the ves­sel.</p>
        <p>Rid­ing point on the nim­ble ves­sel feels like be­ing on a roller coaster, but bet­ter. We ride straight into the surf, jump­ing the waves of pass­ing fer­ries. I taste the ris­ing spray. The ex­pe­ri­ence feels wild and feral – miles from our safely dis­tanced, well­sani­tised gar­den city.</p>
        <p>A 30-minute joyride of­fers a quick sam­pling of the boat’s power, but a 90-minute tour of the South­ern Is­lands, which in­cludes a 20-minute stopover at one is­land, is the com­pany’s most pop­u­lar itin­er­ary. The boat gets up close with un­likely sights, such as the tur­tle hatch­ery on Small Sis­ter’s Is­land that is not open to the pub­lic.</p>
        <p>Closer to the city, Mr Soeigia­rto points out be­he­moth tankers stacked high with ship­ping con­tain­ers (“Your on­line shop­ping,” he says) and a Korean roll-on­roll-off ship, its cargo stacked like match­box col­lectibles.</p>
        <p>To see th­ese ves­sels at close range is to ap­pre­ci­ate their scale and the sheer vol­ume of goods that pass through lo­cal waters ev­ery day.</p>
        <p>Be­yond the ad­ven­ture, it is th­ese sights and knowl­edge that the Soeigia­r­tos hope guests will take away.</p>
        <p>Mr Soeigia­rto says: “When I bring peo­ple out, peo­ple say they are thank­ful they can ex­pe­ri­ence new things here while other coun­tries are ex­pe­ri­enc­ing mul­ti­ple l ock­downs. Sin­ga­pore has strong mar­itime se­cu­rity and her­itage, and I am proud to share this with the world.”</p>

